Title : Lindsay Riches
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}
{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}
'''Lindsay Gordon Riches''', [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]] (18 February 1904 – 7 June 1972) was a South Australian politician. He was a [[Australian Labor Party (South Australian Branch)|Labor Party]] member of the [[South Australian House of Assembly]]  from 1933 to 1970, representing the electorates of [[Electoral district of Newcastle (South Australia)|Newcastle]] (1933-1938) and [[Electoral district of Stuart|Stuart]] (1938-1970). He was [[Speaker of the South Australian House of Assembly]] from 1965 to 1968 under [[Frank Walsh]] and [[Don Dunstan]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/AboutParliament/From1836/Documents/StatisticalRecordoftheLegislature1836to20093.pdf | title=Statistical Register of the Legislature, 1836-2007 | publisher=Parliament of South Australia | accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="parlbio" /> He was also a long-time mayor of the [[City of Port Augusta]] from 1936 to 1970, with Port Augusta gaining city status during his tenure.<ref name="cityhist">{{cite web | url=http://www.portaugusta.sa.gov.au/page.aspx?u=1307&print=1 | title=The 1930s | publisher=City of Port Augusta | accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>

He was born at [[Mundalla, South Australia|Mundalla]], near [[Tatiara, South Australia|Tatiara]], and was educated at Bordertown Public School. He worked as a compositor for the ''[[Border Chronicle]]'' newspaper at [[Bordertown, South Australia|Bordertown]] for seven years after leaving school, working for former state Labor MP [[Donald Campbell (Australian politician)|Donald Campbell]]. He moved to [[Port Augusta, South Australia|Port Augusta]] to work for the ''[[The Transcontinental (Port Augusta)|Transcontinental]]'' in 1924, and took over the operation of that newspaper in 1927, serving as editor.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article212880121 |title=The Two Successful Candidates for Victoria District |newspaper=[[Border Chronicle]] |volume=26, |issue=1285 |location=South Australia |date=14 April 1933 |accessdate=5 June 2016 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article168220568 |title=Mr. Riches M.P, Re-elected |newspaper=[[The Transcontinental (Port Augusta)|Transcontinental]] |location=South Australia |date=25 February 1938 |accessdate=5 June 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=R2TXM0oxIk0C&pg=PA182&lpg=PA182&dq=lindsay+gordon+riches+cmg&source=bl&ots=CPbXySEhyY&sig=Nee8bQfluxNDgryRtUM0dhugj5I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSivzygJDNAhWGnZQKHb0ZBHwQ6AEIKzAD#v=onepage&q=lindsay%20gordon%20riches%20cmg&f=false | title=Responsible Government in South Australia, Volume 2: Playford to Rann | publisher=Wakefield Press | author=Martin, Robert | year=2009 | pages=182}}</ref><ref name="civrecord1936">{{cite book | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-11350397/view#page/n363/mode/1up | title=The Official civic record of South Australia : centenary year, 1936 | publisher=Universal Publicity Company | author=Hosking, P. | year=1936 | location=Adelaide | pages=359}}</ref>

==Honours==
He was appointed [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]] on 1 January 1967 and [[Venerable Order of Saint John|C.St.J.]] on 8 January 1970.<ref name="parlbio">{{cite web | url=http://www2.parliament.sa.gov.au/formermembers/Detail.aspx?pid=3822 | title=Hon Lindsay Riches | publisher=Parliament of South Australia | accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>

